| Notes                   = * Right after the release of {{sl|Spider-Man: Far From Home}}, negotiations between [[Marvel Studios]] and Sony Pictures largely regarding the shares of the revenue of the ''Spider-Man'' films broke down, thus ending Sony's deal to have [[Peter Parker (Earth-199999)|Spider-Man]] appear in the [[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]].{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/sony-fires-back-at-marvel-spider-man-movie-divorce-1233490|title='Spider-Man' Studio Sony Goes Public With Marvel Movie Divorce: "We Are Disappointed" (Exclusive)|first=Borys|last=Kit|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=20 August 2019|accessdate=25 February 2021}} Due to the fan backlash and {{WP|Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland}}'s pleading with the then-Disney CEO {{WP|Bob Iger}}, negotiations were resumed a few weeks later.{{cite|ref=true |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/sony-walt-disneys-marvel-team-on-third-spider-man-homecoming-title-with-superhero-to-appear-in-future-marvel-pics-1202746497/|title=Spider-Man Back In Action As Sony Agrees To Disney Co-Fi For New Movie, Return To MCU: How Spidey’s Web Got Untangled|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|work=Deadline|date=27 September 2019|accessdate=25 February 2021}} At the end of September 2019, the two companies announced that they'd continue their collaboration for a third ''Spider-Man'' film and another MCU movie where Spider-Man would appear.<ref name="Spider-Man Return"/>
* Originally scheduled with the American release date of July 16, 2021,<ref name="Spider-Man Return"/> it was pushed back to November 5, 2021,{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/spider-man-sequel-delays-release-november-2021-sony-date-shuffle-1291805|title='Spider-Man' Sequel Delays Release to November 2021 Amid Sony Date Shuffle|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|coauthors=Couch, Aaron|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=24 April 2020|accessdate=25 February 2021}} then again to December 17, 2021, due to the {{WP|COVID-19 pandemic}}.{{cite|ref=true |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/spider-man-far-from-home-sequel-delayed-1234715451/|title=‘Spider-Man: Far From Home’ Sequel Delayed to December 2021|first=Jordan|last=Moreau|work=Variety|date=23 July 2020|accessdate=25 February 2021}}
* Filming started on October 16 2020, in Queens.
* The title of the film was revealed via Twitter by Sony on February 24, 2021.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://twitter.com/SpiderManMovie/status/1364631273226919937|title=This, we can confirm. #SpiderManNoWayHome only in movie theaters this Christmas.|work=Twitter|date=24 February 2021|accessdate=24 February 2021}}
* The post-credits scene is the first trailer for {{sl|Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness}}.

| Trivia                  = *A lot of quotes and scenes in this movie are direct references to scenes from previous Spider-Man movies, namely those directed by [[Sam Raimi]] and [[Marc Webb]].
** When held in captivity, Osborn tells Parker that he can help him saying ''I'm something of a scientist myself''. This quote is lifted directly from {{sl|Spider-Man (2002 film)}} where Osborn says the same quote to [[Peter Parker (Earth-96283)|Peter-Two]].
** Similarly, Octavius is quoted multiple times as saying ''The power of the sun, in the palm of my hand'', a phrase he commonly used to describe his reactor in {{sl|Spider-Man 2 (film)}}.
** As MJ is falling from the Statue of Liberty, Parker initially fails in catching her but she is instead caught by [[Peter Parker (Earth-120703)|Peter-Three]]. This is a reference to {{sl|The Amazing Spider-Man 2 (film)}} in which Peter-Three failed to catch [[Gwendolyne Stacy (Earth-120703)|Gwen Stacy]].

